HEADWORD: Oxford
<hw>Ox"ford</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>prop. a.</pos> <def>Of or pertaining
to the city or university of Oxford, England.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Oxford movement</b></col>. <cd>See
<er>Tractarianism</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Oxford School</b></col>, <cd>a
name given to those members of the Church of England who adopted the
theology of the so-called Oxford ⟦ldquo⟧Tracts for the Times,⟦rdquo⟧
issued the period 1833 -- 1841.</cd> <au>Shipley.</au> -- <col><b>Oxford
tie</b></col>, <cd>a kind of shoe, laced on the instep, and usually
covering the foot nearly to the ankle.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

